# Git Commit Style

## Format

```
[scope]: Imperative subject, ≤50 chars
```

Use the **hostname** as scope when the change primarily affects one machine (`mike:`, `gila:`, `bes:`, `barbie:`, `desktop:`, `lovelace:`). Use a module or domain name for cross-cutting changes (`tlp:`, `common:`, `hosts:`, `overlays:`). A conventional commit type prefix is also acceptable when it adds signal: `fix(mike):`, `perf(mike):`, `feat(hosts):`.

Subject line rules: imperative mood, ≤50 chars, capitalise the first word after the prefix, no trailing period. Test: "If applied, this commit will `<subject>`."

## Body

Write a body whenever the reason for the change is not immediately obvious from the diff. The body must explain **why** — the problem that existed before, why this approach was chosen, and any unintuitive consequences. Do not narrate what the diff already shows; the reader can see that. Wrap at 72 characters.

```
mike: Throttle nix daemon build jobs

Nix was consuming all CPU cores during builds, making the desktop
completely unresponsive. Limiting build jobs to 4 keeps the system
usable while a build is in progress.
```

## Atomicity and Staging

- One logical unit of change per commit
- Never use `git add .` or `git add -A`
- Stage files explicitly by path: `git add modules/foo.nix modules/bar.nix`
- Run `git status` before staging to confirm only your expected files are touched
